Here's the full step-by-step, based on exactly how I ran it against your existing KVM testbed.

Prerequisites (already satisfied on your box)

• KVM testbed  vms-kvm-t0  is up with DUT  vlab-01  and PTF  ptf_vms6-1  running (confirmed via  virsh list --all  /  docker ps ).
• The  sonic-mgmt  container has  /data  bind-mounted to your host, so your branch/edits are visible inside it automatically.

1. Enter the sonic-mgmt container

docker exec -it sonic-mgmt bash

2. Set required Ansible env vars

export BASE_PATH="/data/sonic-mgmt"
export ANSIBLE_CONFIG=${BASE_PATH}/ansible
export ANSIBLE_HOME=${BASE_PATH}/ansible
export ANSIBLE_LIBRARY=${BASE_PATH}/ansible/library/
export ANSIBLE_MODULE_UTILS=${BASE_PATH}/ansible/module_utils
export ANSIBLE_ACTION_PLUGINS=${BASE_PATH}/ansible/plugins/action
export ANSIBLE_CONNECTION_PLUGINS=${BASE_PATH}/ansible/plugins/connection
export ANSIBLE_CLICONF_PLUGINS=${BASE_PATH}/ansible/cliconf_plugins
export ANSIBLE_TERMINAL_PLUGINS=${BASE_PATH}/ansible/terminal_plugins

3. (One-time) fix git ownership if needed

git config --global --add safe.directory /data/sonic-mgmt

4. Sanity-check the DUT is reachable

cd /data/sonic-mgmt/ansible
ansible -m ping -i veos_vtb vlab-01

Expect  "ping": "pong" .

5. Run the ORAS tests (default = local self-hosted registry, no creds needed)

cd /data/sonic-mgmt/tests

# Just one test
python3 -m pytest -q gnmi/test_gnoi_oras.py::test_gnoi_oras_pull_basic_auth \
  --inventory ../ansible/veos_vtb \
  --host-pattern all \
  --testbed_file vtestbed.yaml \
  --testbed vms-kvm-t0 \
  --log-cli-level info \
  --skip_sanity \
  --disable_loganalyzer \
  -rav

# Whole file
python3 -m pytest -q gnmi/test_gnoi_oras.py \
  --inventory ../ansible/veos_vtb \
  --host-pattern all \
  --testbed_file vtestbed.yaml \
  --testbed vms-kvm-t0 \
  --log-cli-level info \
  --skip_sanity \
  --disable_loganalyzer \
  -rav

 --skip_sanity  and  --disable_loganalyzer  just speed things up for iterative debugging — drop them for a "real" CI-equivalent run.

6. (Optional) Run against a real external registry instead

python3 -m pytest -q gnmi/test_gnoi_oras.py \
  --inventory ../ansible/veos_vtb \
  --host-pattern all \
  --testbed_file vtestbed.yaml \
  --testbed vms-kvm-t0 \
  --oras_test_registry myregistry.azurecr.io \
  --oras_test_repository sonic-os-images \
  --oras_test_tag some-tag \
  --oras_test_username myuser \
  -rav

Password is never a CLI flag — it must come from the vaulted  oras_registry_password  key in that testbed's Ansible  secrets.yml / secrets.json  (via  creds_on_dut ). If it's missing, external-mode tests skip cleanly.

Notes on what to expect

• Local mode spins up  registry_server.py  on the PTF host, pushes a throwaway 1 MiB artifact, trusts its CA inside the DUT's  gnmi  container, runs the pull, then tears everything down — fully hermetic, no internet/secrets required.
• You may see a teardown  ERROR  from the unrelated  gnmi_tls  fixture ( Not all critical processes are healthy , caused by  dhcp_relay  being disabled on this KVM DUT) — that's a known pre-existing KVM flake, not related to the ORAS test itself; the actual test result ( PASSED / SKIPPED / FAILED ) is what matters.
• Collection-only check if you just want to confirm nothing is broken without a full run:
python3 -m pytest --collect-only -q gnmi/test_gnoi_oras.py \
  --inventory ../ansible/veos_vtb --host-pattern all \
  --testbed_file vtestbed.yaml --testbed vms-kvm-t0







































